# Nginx SSL/TLS Configuration

SSL/TLS encrypts traffic between clients and nginx. Nginx handles SSL termination — decrypting incoming HTTPS requests and forwarding plain HTTP to backends. This is the standard pattern for production deployments.

## Quick Start: HTTPS with Let's Encrypt

```bash
# Install certbot
sudo apt install certbot python3-certbot-nginx

# Obtain certificate and auto-configure nginx
sudo certbot --nginx -d example.com -d www.example.com

# Auto-renewal is set up via systemd timer
sudo systemctl status certbot.timer
```

## Manual SSL Configuration

```nginx
server {
    listen 443 ssl;
    listen [::]:443 ssl;
    server_name example.com;

    # Certificates
    ssl_certificate /etc/letsencrypt/live/example.com/fullchain.pem;
    ssl_certificate_key /etc/letsencrypt/live/example.com/privkey.pem;

    # Protocols — only TLS 1.2 and 1.3
    ssl_protocols TLSv1.2 TLSv1.3;

    # Ciphers
    ssl_ciphers HIGH:!aNULL:!MD5;
    ssl_prefer_server_ciphers off;  # let client choose for TLS 1.3

    # Session caching
    ssl_session_cache shared:SSL:10m;
    ssl_session_timeout 10m;
    ssl_session_tickets on;

    # OCSP stapling
    ssl_stapling on;
    ssl_stapling_verify on;
    ssl_trusted_certificate /etc/letsencrypt/live/example.com/chain.pem;
    resolver 8.8.8.8 8.8.4.4 valid=300s;
    resolver_timeout 5s;

    # HSTS (1 year, include subdomains)
    add_header Strict-Transport-Security "max-age=31536000; includeSubDomains" always;

    # Proxy to backend
    location / {
        proxy_pass http://127.0.0.1:3000;
        proxy_set_header Host $host;
        proxy_set_header X-Real-IP $remote_addr;
        proxy_set_header X-Forwarded-For $proxy_add_x_forwarded_for;
        proxy_set_header X-Forwarded-Proto $scheme;
    }
}

# HTTP → HTTPS redirect
server {
    listen 80;
    listen [::]:80;
    server_name example.com www.example.com;
    return 301 https://$host$request_uri;
}
```

## SSL Directives Reference

| Directive | Default | Description |
|-----------|---------|-------------|
| `ssl_certificate` | — | Path to certificate file (PEM) with chain |
| `ssl_certificate_key` | — | Path to private key file (PEM) |
| `ssl_protocols` | `TLSv1.2 TLSv1.3` | Allowed TLS protocol versions |
| `ssl_ciphers` | `HIGH:!aNULL:!MD5` | Allowed cipher suites |
| `ssl_prefer_server_ciphers` | `off` | Prefer server's cipher order |
| `ssl_session_cache` | `none` | Session cache type and size |
| `ssl_session_timeout` | `5m` | Session reuse duration |
| `ssl_session_tickets` | `on` | TLS session ticket resumption |
| `ssl_stapling` | `off` | OCSP stapling |
| `ssl_stapling_verify` | `off` | Verify OCSP responses |
| `ssl_trusted_certificate` | — | CA chain for OCSP and client verification |
| `ssl_dhparam` | — | DH parameters file |
| `ssl_ecdh_curve` | `auto` | ECDH curves |
| `ssl_buffer_size` | `16k` | SSL send buffer (smaller = lower TTFB) |
| `ssl_early_data` | `off` | TLS 1.3 0-RTT (replay risk) |

## Certificate File Formats

```
ssl_certificate = server cert + intermediate cert(s) concatenated
ssl_certificate_key = private key only
ssl_trusted_certificate = intermediate + root CA (for OCSP stapling)
```

Let's Encrypt provides:
- `fullchain.pem` → use as `ssl_certificate`
- `privkey.pem` → use as `ssl_certificate_key`
- `chain.pem` → use as `ssl_trusted_certificate`

## Self-Signed Certificate (Development)

```bash
# Generate self-signed cert valid for 365 days
openssl req -x509 -nodes -days 365 -newkey rsa:2048 \
  -keyout /etc/nginx/ssl/selfsigned.key \
  -out /etc/nginx/ssl/selfsigned.crt \
  -subj "/C=US/ST=State/L=City/O=Dev/CN=localhost"

# Generate DH parameters (optional, for extra security)
openssl dhparam -out /etc/nginx/ssl/dhparam.pem 2048
```

## Dual Certificate (RSA + ECDSA)

```nginx
server {
    listen 443 ssl;
    server_name example.com;

    # RSA certificate
    ssl_certificate /etc/nginx/ssl/example.com.rsa.crt;
    ssl_certificate_key /etc/nginx/ssl/example.com.rsa.key;

    # ECDSA certificate
    ssl_certificate /etc/nginx/ssl/example.com.ecdsa.crt;
    ssl_certificate_key /etc/nginx/ssl/example.com.ecdsa.key;

    ssl_protocols TLSv1.2 TLSv1.3;
}
```

## Security Headers

```nginx
# Add alongside SSL configuration
add_header Strict-Transport-Security "max-age=31536000; includeSubDomains; preload" always;
add_header X-Content-Type-Options nosniff always;
add_header X-Frame-Options DENY always;
add_header X-XSS-Protection "1; mode=block" always;
add_header Referrer-Policy strict-origin-when-cross-origin always;
```

## Let's Encrypt Automation

```bash
# Initial setup
sudo certbot --nginx -d example.com -d www.example.com --non-interactive --agree-tos -m admin@example.com

# Test renewal
sudo certbot renew --dry-run

# Force renewal
sudo certbot renew --force-renewal

# Certificate locations
ls /etc/letsencrypt/live/example.com/
# cert.pem  chain.pem  fullchain.pem  privkey.pem

# Certbot auto-adds reload hook: nginx -s reload
```

## Testing SSL Configuration

```bash
# Check certificate details
openssl s_client -connect example.com:443 -servername example.com </dev/null 2>/dev/null | openssl x509 -text -noout

# Check expiration date
openssl s_client -connect example.com:443 -servername example.com </dev/null 2>/dev/null | openssl x509 -enddate -noout

# Test specific TLS version
openssl s_client -connect example.com:443 -tls1_2
openssl s_client -connect example.com:443 -tls1_3

# Full SSL test
curl -vI https://example.com 2>&1 | grep -E 'SSL|TLS|certificate'
```
